Nonlinear Gaussian regression

  1. We will first calculate \(p\left(\beta \mid x, y, \sigma^{2}, \gamma\right)\) using the fact that \[ p\left(\beta \mid x, y, \sigma^{2}, \gamma\right) \propto f(y;x,\sigma^{2}, \gamma,\beta)p(\beta |\sigma^2) \] Define \(\beta = (\beta_0, \beta_1)\) and \(G\) the vector \(G = (1,g(x_i,\gamma))\) where \(g\left(x_{i}, \gamma\right)=x_{i} /\left(\gamma+x_{i}\right)\) for \(\beta \in \mathbb{R}^{2}, \gamma \in \mathbb{R} \text { and } \sigma^{2} \in \mathbb{R}^{+}\). We know that \(y_{i} \mid x_{i}, \beta, \gamma, \sigma^{2} \sim N\left(\beta_{0}+\beta_{1} g\left(x_{i}, \gamma\right), \sigma^{2}\right)\) and \(\beta \mid \sigma^{2} \sim N\left(b_{0}, \sigma^{2} B_{0}\right)\), where \(b_{0}=(50,170)^{\prime}, B_{0}=3 I_{2}\). Writing in matrix notation we have

\[ \begin{align} l(y;x,\sigma^{2}, \gamma,\beta) &= f(y;x,\sigma^{2}, \gamma,\beta) \\ & \propto (\sigma^{-2})^{-n / 2} \exp \left\{-\frac{\sigma^{-2}}{2}(y-G \beta)^{\prime}(y-G \beta)\right\} \\ & \propto (\sigma^{-2})^{-n / 2} \exp \left\{-\frac{\sigma^{-2}}{2}((\beta-\hat{\beta})^{\prime} G^{\prime} G(\beta-\hat{\beta}) + S_e)\right\} \end{align} \] where \(\hat{\beta} = (G'G)^{-1}G'y\) and \(S_e = (y-G \hat{\beta})^{\prime}(y-G \hat{\beta}) = \sum_{i=1}^{n} e_{i}^{2}\).

Combining now with the prior for \(\beta | \sigma^2\) we have \[ \begin{align} p\left(\beta \mid x, y, \sigma^{2}, \gamma\right) &\propto (\sigma^{-2})^{-d / 2} \exp \left\{-\frac{\sigma^{-2}}{2}((\beta-\hat{\beta})^{\prime} G^{\prime} G(\beta-\hat{\beta}) + S_e)\right\} \\ &\times (\sigma^{-2})^{-n / 2} \exp \left\{-\frac{\sigma^{-2}}{2}\left[\left(\beta-b_{0}\right)^{\prime} B_{0}^{-1}\left(\beta-b_{0}\right)\right]\right\} \\ & \propto (\sigma^{-2})^{-(d +n )/ 2} \exp \left\{-\frac{\sigma^{-2}}{2}\left((\beta-\hat{\beta})^{\prime} G^{\prime} G(\beta-\hat{\beta}) + S_e + \left(\beta-b_{0}\right)^{\prime} B_{0}^{-1}\left(\beta-b_{0}\right)\right) \right\} \end{align} \]

  1. Now Ill show that \(p\left(\sigma^{2} \mid x, y, \beta, \gamma\right)\) follows an Inverse-Gamma distribution. \[ p\left(\sigma^{2} \mid x, y, \beta, \gamma\right) \propto f(y;x,\sigma^{2}, \gamma,\beta)p(\sigma^2) \]

hence

\[\begin{align} p\left(\sigma^{2} \mid x, y, \beta, \gamma\right) &\propto (\sigma^{-2})^{n/2}\exp \left\{-\frac{1}{2 \sigma^{2}}\left[\beta_{1}^{2} \sum_{i=1}^{n} g^{2}\left(x_{i}, \gamma\right)-2\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(y_{i}-\beta_{0}\right) g\left(x_{i}, \gamma\right)\right]\right\} \\ & \times (\sigma^2)^{-\alpha_1-1}exp\left\{\dfrac{-\alpha_2}{\sigma^2} \right\} \\ p\left(\sigma^{2} \mid x, y, \beta, \gamma\right) &\propto (\sigma^2)^{-(\alpha_1+n/2)-1}exp\left\{-\dfrac{\alpha_2+\beta_{1}^{2}/2 \sum_{i=1}^{n} g^{2}(x_{i}, \gamma)-\sum_{i=1}^{n}(y_{i}-\beta_{0})g(x_{i}, \gamma)}{\sigma^2}\right\} \\ p\left(\sigma^{2} \mid x, y, \beta, \gamma\right) &\propto (\sigma^2)^{-\alpha_{post}-1}exp\left\{-\dfrac{\beta_{post}}{\sigma^2} \right\} \end{align}\]

where

\[\begin{align} \alpha_{post} &= \alpha_1+n/2 \\ \beta_{post} &=\alpha_2+\beta_{1}^{2}/2 \sum_{i=1}^{n} g^{2}(x_{i}, \gamma)-\sum_{i=1}^{n}(y_{i}-\beta_{0})g(x_{i}, \gamma) \end{align}\]

  1. Ill now calculate \(p\left(\sigma^{2} \mid x, y, \gamma\right)\), since the prior of \(\beta\) is conditional on \(\sigma^2\), \(p\left(\sigma^{2} \mid x, y, \gamma\right)\) is also an Inverse-Gamma. Using matrix notation we have that \[ p\left(\sigma^{2},\beta \mid x, y, \gamma\right) \propto f(y;x,\sigma^{2}, \gamma,\beta)p(\beta |\sigma^2)p(\sigma^2) \] hence, using the derivation in item (a) and the prior for \(\sigma^2\)

\[ \begin{align} p\left(\sigma^{2},\beta \mid x, y, \gamma\right) &\propto (\sigma^{-2})^{-d / 2} \exp \left\{-\frac{\sigma^{-2}}{2}((\beta-\hat{\beta})^{\prime} G^{\prime} G(\beta-\hat{\beta}) + S_e)\right\} \\ &\times (\sigma^{-2})^{-n / 2} \exp \left\{-\frac{\sigma^{-2}}{2}\left[\left(\beta-b_{0}\right)^{\prime} B_{0}^{-1}\left(\beta-b_{0}\right)\right]\right\}(\sigma^{-2})^{\left(v_{0} / 2\right)-1} \exp \left\{-\frac{\sigma^{-2}}{2} v_{0} \sigma^{-2}_{0}\right\} \\ & \propto (\sigma^{-2})^{-(d +n +v_0)/ 2-1} \exp \left\{-\frac{\sigma^{-2}}{2}\left((\beta-\hat{\beta})^{\prime} G^{\prime} G(\beta-\hat{\beta}) + S_e + \left(\beta-b_{0}\right)^{\prime} B_{0}^{-1}\left(\beta-b_{0}\right)\right) + v_0\sigma^{-2}_{0} \right\} \end{align} \] and the expression above is equivalente to \[ p\left(\sigma^{2},\beta \mid x, y, \gamma\right) \propto (\sigma^{-2})^{\frac{d}{2}} \exp \left\{-\frac{\sigma^{-2}}{2}\left(\beta-b_{1}\right)^{\prime} B_{1}^{-1}\left(\beta-b_{1}\right)\right\} (\sigma^{-2})^{\frac{n_{1}}{2}-1} \exp \left\{-\frac{\sigma^{-2}}{2} n_{1} \sigma^{2}_{1}\right\} \] where \(n_1 = v_0 + n\), \(n_1\sigma_1^{2} = v_{0} \sigma^{2}_{0}+\left(y-G b_{1}\right)^{\prime} y+\left(b_{0}-b_{1}\right)^{\prime} B_{0}^{-1} b_{0}\), \(b_1 = B_{1}\left(B_{0}^{-1} b_{0}+G^{\prime} y\right)\) and \(B_{1}^{-1}=B_{0}^{-1}+G^{\prime} G\). Computing the posterior in terms of \(\sigma^2\) we have the Inverse-Gamma distribution with \(\alpha_1 = n_1/2\) and \(\alpha_2 = \dfrac{n_1\sigma^2_1}{2}\).

  1. MCMC algorithm that cycles through the full conditionals:

Gibbs sample of \(\sigma^2\) from \(p\left(\sigma^{2} \mid x, y, \beta, \gamma\right)\). Recall that \(p\left(\sigma^{2} \mid x, y, \beta, \gamma\right)\) is an Inverse-Gamma distribution as derived in item (b), hence

\[\begin{align} p\left(\sigma^{2} \mid x, y, \beta, \gamma\right) & \propto (\sigma^2)^{-\alpha_{post}-1}exp\left\{-\dfrac{\beta_{post}}{\sigma^2}\right\} \end{align}\]

where

\[ \begin{align} \alpha_{post} &= \alpha_1+n/2 \\ \beta_{post} &=\alpha_2+\beta_{1}^{2}/2 \sum_{i=1}^{n} g^{2}(x_{i}, \gamma)-\sum_{i=1}^{n}(y_{i}-\beta_{0}g(x_{i}, \gamma)) \end{align} \]

require("mvtnorm")
## Loading required package: mvtnorm
library("mvtnorm")

x = c(0.02,0.02,0.06,0.06,0.11,0.11,0.22,0.22,0.56,0.56,1.10,1.10)
y = c(76,47,97,107,123,139,159,152,191,201,207,200)
plot(x,y)

# Initial data
n = length(y)
d = length(x)
sig2.0 = 10
nu.0 = 5
nu.1 = nu.0+n
tau20 = 1
beta0.0 = 50
beta1.0 = 170
beta.0 = c(beta0.0,beta1.0)
beta.d = beta.0
B0 = diag(3,2)
iB0 = solve(B0)
b0 = rep(0,2)
iB0b0 = iB0%*%b0
gamma.d = 0
gamma.0 = 0

#Defining functions
mu      = function(gamma,x){beta.d[1]+beta.d[2]*x/(gamma+x)}
loglike = function(gamma){sum(dnorm(y,mu(gamma,x),sqrt(sig2.d),log=TRUE))}

set.seed(12345)
burnin = 10000
M      = 10000
niter  = burnin+M
draws  = matrix(0,niter,4)
 
# Cycling through the full conditionals
runtime = system.time({
for (iter in 1:niter){

g = x/(x+gamma.d)
G = cbind(1,g)
#g2 = sum((x/(gamma.d+x))^2)
#f = sum((y-beta.d[1])*x/(gamma.d+x))
#sig2.d = 1/rgamma(1,nu.0+n/2,nu.0*sig2.0/2+beta.d[2]^2/2*g2-f)
sig2.d = 1/rgamma(1,nu.0+n/2,nu.0*sig2.0/2+t(y-G%*%beta.d)%*%(y-G%*%beta.d)/2)

B1 = solve(iB0+t(G)%*%G)
b1 = B1%*%(iB0b0+t(G)%*%y)
beta.d = as.vector(rmvnorm(1,b1,sig2.d*B1))

# Metropolis-Hastings
gam = rnorm(1,gamma.d,0.005) 
num = dnorm(gam,gamma.0,tau20,log=TRUE)+loglike(gam)
den = dnorm(gamma.d,gamma.0,tau20,log=TRUE)+loglike(gamma.d)

accept = exp(num-den)
  if (runif(1) < accept){
    gamma.d = gam }
       
draws[iter,] = c(beta.d,sig2.d,gamma.d)
}})
draws = draws[(burnin+1):niter,]
means = colMeans(draws); mean.beta0.d = means[1];mean.beta1.d = means[2];mean.sig2.d = means[3];mean.gamma.d = means[4]

# Cycling through the full conditionals
